        "header": "3Method",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2605.30332/2605.30332v1/x1.png",
                "caption": "Figure 2:PSD of different colored noises. The spectra transition smoothly from high-frequency dominantblue noise, through uniform white noise (center black line), to low-frequency dominantred noise.",
                "position": 545
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2605.30332/2605.30332v1/x2.png",
                "caption": "Figure 3:Temporal progression of frequency bands during sampling.",
                "position": 588
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2605.30332/2605.30332v1/x3.png",
                "caption": "Figure 4:The Spectral Gap Across Sampling Methods.(Left)PSDs of the generated distributions versus the PSD of the ground truth ImageNet. Standard ODE sampling over-generates low-frequency structures and under-generates high-frequency details, while standard SDE sampling exhibits an energy deficit across the entire spectrum.(Right)The signedlog10\\log_{10}error relative to the ground truth (black dashed line). By dynamically reallocating the injected noise budget, CNS better aligns the generated spectrum with the true data manifold, mitigating the spectral gap and achieving the lowest log-space Mean Absolute Error (MAE) across frequencies.",
                "position": 627
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2605.30332/2605.30332v1/x4.png",
                "caption": "Figure 5:Noise Signal Preservation and Transfer.(Left)Initial Noise Persistence. Cosine similarity between initial noise and the final generated image. ODEs strongly preserve structural information across the spectrum; stochastic methods (SDE, CNS) still retain a significant, though reduced, amount of this initial signal.(Right)Cumulative Injection Transfer. Cosine similarity between total injected noise (ϵcumul\\epsilon_{\\text{cumul}}) and the final generated image. This shows injected noise structure actively shapes the final features rather than serving as a temporary perturbation. Notably, CNS selectively routes this signal into higher frequency bands.",
                "position": 660
            },
            {
